{{Infobox officeholder | name =Mariya Didi | native_name =މާރިޔާ އަހްމަދު ދީދީ | image = | office1 = Minister of Defence | president1 = [[Ibrahim Mohamed Solih]] | predecessor1 = [[Adam Shareef]] | successor1= | office2 = Machchangolhi North constituency | predecessor2 =''office established'' | successor2= ''vacant'' | term_start2 = 9 May 2009 | term_end2 = 17 November 2018 | term_start1 = 17 November 2018 | term_end1 = | party = [[Maldivian Democratic Party]] | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1963|08|18}} | death_date = | death_place = | death_cause = | resting_place = | nationality = [[Maldives|Maldivian]] | spouse = | children = 1 daughter, 2 sons }}
Mariya Didi is the incumbent Minister of Defence of the Republic of Maldives, a former Member of Parliament and a leading human rights activist. She was sworn in as the Minister of Defence on 17th November 2018 by His Excellency President Ibrahim Mohamed Solih. She holds the distinction of being the first female in the history of Maldives to be appointed as the Minister of Defence. Minister Mariya has a Bachelor’s degree in Law (LLB) (Hons) and a Master’s degree in Law (LLB) (Hons) from the University of Aberystwyth, Wales, United Kingdom. She completed her professional qualifications in England and is among the first two Barristers to be called to the Bar of England and Wales, and is a Barrister of the prestigious Gray’s Inn, England, having done her pupillage at Albion Chambers, Bristol. Mariya believes that her studies laid the foundations that in order for a country to become a nation of laws and enjoy all freedoms that come along with it, democracy and the rule of law have to be introduced, nurtured and allowed to flourish. Minister Mariya is the first female lawyer of the Maldives. She is one of the few female members of parliament the world over, who has succeeded in sitting in Parliament for four Consecutive terms. As an elected Member of Parliament, Mariya Didi sat in the Constitutional Assembly that amended the 1998 Constitution, which laid foundation for the democracy in the Maldives. She was also a Member of the drafting Committee of the 2008 Constitution. Minister Mariya is the first and the only woman so far to be elected as Chairperson of a major political party in the Maldives. She was elected as Chairperson of the largest political party in the Maldives - the MDP. It was under her chairmanship that the party won the first ever multiparty democratic presidential elections held in the Maldives in 2008. She was awarded the International Women of Courage Award by the US Secretary of State in recognition of her contribution to democracy and human rights in the Maldives. Minister Mariya is married to Mr. Mohamed Amir. She is blessed with one daughter and two son
